{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"378fd07e-0eee-465c-9aee-97685ae1008e","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe developer report confirms the overhead is **MSBuild process startup + project re-evaluation**, not compilation. This is because `dotnet build` differs from Visual Studio in two critical ways:\n\n| Setting | Visual Studio | `dotnet build` (default) |\n|---|---|---|\n| MSBuild node reuse | **Enabled** (nodes stay alive) | **Disabled** (`-nodeReuse:false`) |\n| Roslyn shared compiler | **Enabled** (VBCSCompiler persists) | **Disabled** |\n\nEvery `dotnet build` invocation pays a cold-start tax that VS avoids entirely.\n\n## Recommendations (fastest → most involved)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop (biggest win, zero config)\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\nThis keeps the build process alive and rebuilds on file changes — closest to the VS experience.\n\n### 2. Enable MSBuild node reuse + shared compilation\nAdd to your shell profile (`.bashrc`, `.zshrc`, etc.):\n```bash\nexport MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0\nexport UseSharedCompilation=true\n```\nThen build with:\n```bash\ndotnet build -nodeReuse:true\n```\nThis keeps MSBuild worker nodes and the Roslyn compiler server alive between builds, eliminating startup overhead on subsequent runs.\n\n### 3. Enable the MSBuild Build Server (.NET 8+)\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nThis uses a long-running MSBuild server process — the same architecture VS uses internally.\n\n### Summary\nThe project file itself is fine — no changes needed there. The slowness is purely a `dotnet` CLI default behavior issue (it kills MSBuild/Roslyn processes after every invocation for CI reproducibility). For dev inner loops, `dotnet watch build` is the simplest fix; environment variables give you parity with VS for ad-hoc `dotnet build` calls.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dd1f65bd-1512-44c3-9ede-485c6b7d4e1f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow (2-4 seconds) for incremental builds even when nothing has changed, while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've already ruled out analyzers and confirmed incremental build targets work correctly. The overhead is from MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses the MSBuild Server (a long-lived MSBuild process) which avoids the cold-start overhead on every build. Starting with .NET 8 / MSBuild 17.9+, there's an opt-in feature called the **MSBuild Server** (also known as `dotnet build-server`) that keeps an MSBuild process running between builds, avoiding repeated startup and project evaluation costs.\n\n\nThe main solution is enabling the MSBuild Build Server by setting `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or using the `-nodeReuse:true` flag, which keeps an MSBuild node alive between builds to eliminate cold-start overhead. The most practical solution here is using `dotnet watch` for the development loop—it keeps the MSBuild process alive between builds and watches for file changes, which is far more efficient than rebuilding from scratch each time. I should also mention that enabling node reuse with `-nodeReuse:true` helps, since the .NET CLI defaults to shutting down MSBuild processes after each build unlike Visual Studio. The key insight is that the `dotnet` CLI sets `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1` by default, which kills MSBuild nodes after each build—unlike Visual Studio. I can override this with an environment variable or CLI flag to keep nodes alive, and similarly enable the Roslyn compiler server with `UseSharedCompilation=true` to avoid repeated compiler startup costs.\n\nMost of the optimization comes down to developer workflow rather than project configuration: using `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop, setting environment variables to enable node reuse and shared compilation, and potentially creating a shell alias to make this the default. There's not much to change in the `.csproj` itself—it's more about how the build is invoked.","outputTokens":1763,"requestId":"040C:69BE5:41C2B9:4D139E:69F00422"},"id":"1021ae95-21c9-45e8-a805-a30354e2e1f5","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:50:15.698Z","parentId":"01939c53-b11e-458c-8064-f3c8a4aadb36"}
